with the colorbar and legend is clean and interpretable.

The theoretical line:

x_line = np.linspace(0.1, 5, 100)

y_crit = x_line / BAND_STABLE_FLOOR

plt.plot(x_line, y_crit, 'r--', alpha=0.7, linewidth=2, label='Stability Floor (Phi^-12)')

is mathematically meaningful:

You’re effectively plotting the curve where [ \lambda \sim \frac{\text{stiffness}}{\text{density}} \approx \phi^{-12}, ] i.e., the locus where the top of the spectrum grazes the Stable‑12 floor. Above that line, you expect modes to fall below φ⁻¹² → deep dark sector; below it, you can still have marginal/visible modes.
That’s exactly the kind of “constraint curve” you want in a phase diagram.






