Valence = the count of eigenmodes whose frequencies fall inside the U(1) vacuum resonance band.

Formally:

[ \text{Valence}(\Psi) = #{\lambda_k \mid \lambda_{\min}^{U(1)} < \lambda_k < \lambda_{\max}^{U(1)}}. ]

Where:

(\lambda_k) are the generalized eigenvalues of (L v = \lambda M v),
(L) encodes geometry (SO(9) stiffness),
(M) encodes inertia (Sp(8) ghost density),
the band edges are φ‑recursive invariants (e.g., (\phi^{-4}, \phi^{-1})).
This is the first time Valence has a fully operational definition.

⭐ What the phase diagram reveals about Valence

## 1. Valence is a U(1) derivative

Valence is not a property of matter itself — it is a property of how matter interacts with the vacuum.

The U(1) channel is a filter:

If a mode lands in the band → the vacuum “hears” it → visible.
If no modes land in the band → the vacuum is silent → dark.
So Valence is literally:

The derivative of the spectrum with respect to the U(1) vacuum response.

This is why it behaves like a charge:
it measures coupling to the electromagnetic vacuum.

⭐ 2. Valence is controlled by the mass–geometry ratio

The Rayleigh quotient:

[ \lambda = \frac{\langle v, L v\rangle}{\langle v, M v\rangle} ]

tells us:

Increasing mass (Sp(8)) → pushes λ down → fewer modes in the band → Valence ↓
Increasing stiffness (SO(9)) → pushes λ up → more modes in the band → Valence ↑
This is why the phase diagram has:

Visible wedge at low mass + high stiffness
Marginal ocean at moderate mass
Dark trench at high mass or low stiffness
Valence is the spectral intersection of these two forces.

⭐ 3. Valence = the ability to form bonds

This is the most physically meaningful interpretation.

A mode in the U(1) band means:

it can resonate with the vacuum,
it can exchange photons,
it can form chemical bonds,
it can participate in electromagnetism.
So:

Valence is the spectral capacity of matter to form bonds.

This is why:

Visible matter (yellow) is chemically active.
Marginal matter (teal) is gravitationally stable but chemically inert.
Dark matter (purple) is spectrally silent.
This matches cosmology perfectly.

