Chapter 6.2 Summary — Ghost Density Physics
Chapter 6.2 formalizes the spectral mechanics that govern visibility, bonding, and the structure of the dark sector. It introduces Ghost Density Physics as the study of how Sp(8) inertial loading and SO(9) geometric stiffness jointly determine a system’s spectral valence — its ability to resonate with the U(1) vacuum band.

The chapter begins by replacing the discrete “hook-count” model of valence with a rigorous spectral definition:
[ L v = \lambda M v ]

where (L) is the Laplacian (geometry), (M) is the mass matrix (ghost density), and (\lambda) are the vibrational eigenvalues. Valence is defined as the number (or integrated intensity) of eigenmodes that fall within the φ recursive U(1) band:
[ V = \int_{\phi^{-4}}^{\phi^{-1}} \mathcal{D}(\lambda), d\lambda ]

This framework reveals that visibility is not binary — it is a continuous, fractal measure of spectral overlap.

The v13 simulation demonstrates that increasing ghost density compresses the spectrum, pushing modes below the vacuum band and rendering matter invisible. The v14.1 phase diagram maps this transition across a grid of mass and stiffness, revealing three regimes:
•	Visible (Yellow): Low mass, high stiffness — Standard Model matter
•	Marginal (Teal): Moderate mass — structurally stable but spectrally silent
•	Dark (Purple): High mass, low stiffness — sub-sonic matter with no U(1) coupling

The v14.2 simulation refines this further by introducing ensemble averaging and continuous spectral integration. It produces a heatmap of average fractal valence across the phase space, revealing a smooth gradient from visibility to darkness. Two key contours emerge:
•	The Baryonic Frontier (Valence ≈ 0.05): The edge of visibility, matching the observed ~5% baryonic fraction
•	The Integer Core (Valence = 1.0): The stable region of classical chemistry and crystallography
A boxed theorem (Theorem 6.2.B) formalizes the phenomenon of band-edge fractionalization: modes near φ⁻⁴ or φ⁻¹ contribute (V_k \approx 0.5), explaining partial charges, weak bonds, catalytic barriers, and warm dark matter.

Biologically, this chapter shows that life requires the fractal regime. Integer valence would freeze dynamics, preventing hydrogen bonding, conformational changes, and thermal breathing modes. Soft geometry and drifting eigenvalues enable evolvability, and CEC cascades can now be interpreted as valence modulation events.

Finally, the chapter introduces falsifiability hooks:
•	Simulate small molecules (H₂O, CH₄) using realistic graphs and masses
•	Vary thermal noise in (M) to observe integer → fractal transitions
•	Probe warm dark matter by tuning ghost density near φ⁻⁴ and measuring fractional valence
Ghost Density Physics is no longer a metaphor — it is a constraint-first, spectral field theory with falsifiable predictions, biological relevance, and cosmological reach. It establishes valence as a fractal resonance measure and positions the observer as a spectral filter embedded in a narrow wedge of visibility.
This chapter is the foundation for RCFT’s unified treatment of matter, resonance, and emergence.






