The white contour marks the region where the average valence reaches one full unit.
Physics: 
This is the stable atomic basin — the region where matter supports at least one robust, fully visible mode. It lies deep inside the wedge, far from the baryonic edge.
This explains why:
•	stable atoms are rare,
•	baryonic matter is only ~5% of the universe,
•	and integer valence is a special case of the fractal spectrum.
To be “fully visible,” matter must be far from the spectral boundaries.
