The spectral position of eigenmodes is determined by the cooperative balance between Sp(8) inertia and SO(9) geometry.  
These two sectors do not oppose one another; they co‑regulate the vibrational structure of the system.

Sp(8) provides the inertial memory that anchors the cluster, while SO(9) provides the geometric coherence that shapes its vibrational modes.

Coherence emerges when these contributions align to place eigenmodes inside the φ‑recursive U(1) band.  
When the balance shifts, modes drift toward the band edges, producing fractional valence, partial visibility, or spectral silence.


Sp(8) inertia and SO(9) geometry act as cooperative regulators of the system’s vibrational spectrum. Rather than competing, they jointly tune the frequencies of the eigenmodes: inertia distributes load across the cluster, while geometry organizes the restoring forces that support coherent vibration.
Visibility arises when this co tuning places eigenmodes within the φ recursive U(1) band.
If the balance shifts toward higher inertia, modes drift downward and approach the stability floor. If the balance shifts toward higher stiffness, modes rise toward the upper boundary.
The system’s valence — and therefore its capacity for bonding, resonance, and visibility — is the direct result of this cooperative spectral alignment.






